{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17565480","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17565480"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:27:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:27:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17500"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17500","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17500"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.81,0.05,0.04,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10190"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70985"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10190","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10190"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17500"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56454"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1217"},{"type":"tags","id":"2166"},{"type":"tags","id":"4394"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"11176"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"12124"},{"type":"tags","id":"12800"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23852"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43697"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70985","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70985"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the antenatal clinic for a routine visit at 32 weeks gestation. This is her first pregnancy and has been uncomplicated until now. She has no significant medical history and takes only pregnancy supplements. On examination, her fundal height measures large for dates at 36 cm. An ultrasound reveals an amniotic fluid index of 30 cm (normal 5-24 cm). The fetus appears anatomically normal except for two fluid-filled structures in the upper abdomen resembling a \u0027double bubble\u0027 appearance.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following fetal anomalies is most likely to be present?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Tracheo-oesophageal fistula","Duodenal atresia","Gastroschisis","Oesophageal atresia","Jejunal atresia"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with polyhydramnios, which is an excessive accumulation of amniotic fluid. The presence of a \u0027double bubble\u0027 sign on ultrasound is pathognomonic for \u003Cstrong\u003Eduodenal atresia\u003C/strong\u003E. This condition prevents the fetus from swallowing and absorbing amniotic fluid, leading to polyhydramnios in 50% of cases. Duodenal atresia is associated with Down syndrome in approximately 30% of cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOesophageal atresia\u003C/strong\u003E can also cause polyhydramnios due to inability to swallow amniotic fluid, but would show a small or absent stomach bubble rather than a double bubble sign on ultrasound.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGastroschisis\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by herniation of abdominal contents through a defect in the anterior abdominal wall. While it can be associated with polyhydramnios, the ultrasound would show free-floating bowel loops in the amniotic cavity rather than a double bubble sign.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EJejunal atresia\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with multiple dilated loops of small bowel rather than the classic double bubble appearance seen in duodenal atresia. Polyhydramnios is less common with jejunal atresia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETracheo-oesophageal fistula\u003C/strong\u003E may present with polyhydramnios, but the ultrasound would show a small or absent stomach bubble and possibly evidence of aspiration rather than a double bubble sign.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe double bubble sign represents fluid-filled dilated stomach and proximal duodenum, with the remainder of the small bowel being collapsed. This occurs because the duodenal obstruction prevents passage of fluid beyond the point of atresia. Management involves close monitoring of the pregnancy, planned delivery at a tertiary centre, and surgical correction of the atresia in the neonatal period.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Polyhydramnios is defined as amniotic fluid index \u003E24 cm or single deepest pocket \u003E8 cm.","Duodenal atresia causes polyhydramnios due to inability of the fetus to swallow and absorb amniotic fluid.","The \u0027double bubble\u0027 sign on antenatal ultrasound is pathognomonic for duodenal atresia."],"references":["Pariente G, Landau D, Aviram M, Hershkovitz R. Prenatal diagnosis of a rare sonographic appearance of duodenal atresia: report of 2 cases and literature review. J Ultrasound Med. 2012 Nov;31(11):1829-33. doi: 10.7863/jum.2012.31.11.1829. PMID: 23091256.","Duodenal atresia. Osmosis. [Internet]. [cited 2024 Jun 16]. Available from: https://www.osmosis.org/answers/duodenal-atresia"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56454"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17500"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56454","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56454"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-16T17:48:19+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-16T17:48:53+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10190"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70985"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"O